Two Decades of Amazon Equity Insights¶

1. CAGR of Amazon’s Stock (2000–2023)¶

In [15]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("Amazon stock data 2000-2025.csv")

# Step 1: Convert to datetime (force timezone-naive)
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'], errors='coerce', utc=True).dt.tz_localize(None)

# Step 2: Drop invalid dates
df = df.dropna(subset=['date'])

# Step 3: Sort and verify
df = df.sort_values('date')
print(df['date'].dtype)  # Confirm: datetime64[ns]

# Calculate CAGR
start_price = df[df['date'].dt.year == 2000]['adj_close'].iloc[0]
end_price = df[df['date'].dt.year == 2023]['adj_close'].iloc[-1]
years = 2023 - 2000
cagr = (end_price / start_price) ** (1/years) - 1

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df['date'], df['adj_close'], color='navy')
plt.title(f'CAGR: {cagr:.2%}')
plt.savefig("CACR.png")
plt.show()

datetime64[ns]

2. Annualized Volatility & Event Correlation¶

In [19]:
# Calculate volatility
df['Daily Return'] = df['adj_close'].pct_change()

# Use the correct date column name (e.g., 'date' instead of 'Date')
annual_vol = df.groupby(df['date'].dt.year)['Daily Return'].std() * (252**0.5)

# Bar chart with events
events = {2008: '2008 Crisis', 2020: 'COVID-19'}
colors = ['red' if year in events else 'skyblue' for year in annual_vol.index]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.bar(annual_vol.index.astype(str), annual_vol, color=colors)
plt.title('Annualized Volatility')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Volatility (σ)')
for year, label in events.items():
    plt.text(str(year), annual_vol.loc[year], label, ha='center', va='bottom')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.savefig("annualized volatility.png")
plt.show()

3. Moving Average Crossover Strategy¶

# Calculate moving averages
df['50_MA'] = df['adj_close'].rolling(50).mean()
df['200_MA'] = df['adj_close'].rolling(200).mean()

# Line chart
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df['date'], df['adj_close'], label='Price', alpha=0.5)
plt.plot(df['date'], df['50_MA'], label='50-Day MA', color='orange')
plt.plot(df['date'], df['200_MA'], label='200-Day MA', color='green')
plt.title('Moving Average Crossover Strategy')
plt.xlabel('date')
plt.ylabel('Price ($)')
plt.legend()

5. Sharpe Ratio¶

In [28]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Data
sharpe_ratio = 0.52
benchmark = 1.0  # Common "good" Sharpe Ratio threshold

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.bar(['Your Sharpe Ratio', 'Benchmark (1.0)'], [sharpe_ratio, benchmark], 
        color=['#2ca02c', '#d62728'])
plt.axhline(y=0, color='black', linestyle='--')
plt.title('Sharpe Ratio vs Benchmark', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Sharpe Ratio')
plt.text(0, sharpe_ratio + 0.05, f'{sharpe_ratio:.2f}', ha='center', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.3)
plt.savefig("sharpe ratio vs benchmark.png")
plt.show()

7. Seasonality Patterns¶

In [34]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming 'df' has a datetime column 'date'
df['Month'] = df['date'].dt.month
monthly_avg = df.groupby('Month')['Daily Return'].mean()

# Define month names
month_names = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun',
               'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(monthly_avg.index, monthly_avg, marker='o', linestyle='--')
plt.title('Monthly Seasonality')
plt.xticks(range(1, 13), month_names, rotation=45)  # Fixed labels
plt.ylabel('Average Return')
plt.grid(True)
plt.savefig("monthly seasonality.png")
plt.show()

8. Drawdown Analysis¶

In [37]:
df['Rolling Max'] = df['adj_close'].cummax()
df['Drawdown'] = (df['adj_close'] - df['Rolling Max']) / df['Rolling Max']
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.fill_between(df['date'], df['Drawdown'], color='red', alpha=0.3)
plt.title('Maximum Drawdown')
plt.savefig("drawdown analysis.png")

9. ARIMA Forecasting¶

In [39]:
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
train = df['adj_close'].iloc[:-30]
model = ARIMA(train, order=(5,1,0)).fit()
forecast = model.forecast(steps=30)
plt.plot(df['date'], df['adj_close'], label='Actual')
plt.plot(pd.date_range(start=df['date'].iloc[-1], periods=30), forecast, label='Forecast')
plt.title('ARIMA Forecast')
plt.legend()
plt.savefig("ARIMA forecasting.png")
plt.show()

# Calculate Z-Scores for volume anomalies
df['Volume Z-Score'] = (df['volume'] - df['volume'].mean()) / df['volume'].std()
anomalies = df[df['Volume Z-Score'].abs() > 3]

# Plot anomalies
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.scatter(anomalies['date'], anomalies['adj_close'], color='red', label='Volume Anomaly')
plt.plot(df['date'], df['adj_close'], alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Volume Anomalies')
plt.legend()
plt.savefig("volume anomalies.png")

15. Event-Driven Performance (e.g., COVID-19)¶

In [75]:
# Convert 'date' column to UTC datetime
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'], utc=True)

# Filter with UTC-aware dates
covid_period = df[
    (df['date'] >= pd.to_datetime('2020-01-01', utc=True)) & 
    (df['date'] <= pd.to_datetime('2020-12-31', utc=True))
]

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(covid_period['date'], covid_period['adj_close'], marker='o', linestyle='-', color='green')
plt.axvline(pd.to_datetime('2020-03-16', utc=True), color='red', linestyle='--', label='Market Crash')
plt.title('Amazon Stock Performance During COVID-19 (2020)')
plt.xlabel('Date (UTC)')
plt.ylabel('Adjusted Close Price ($)')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.savefig("COVID 19.png")
plt.show()
